        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to write a balance confirmation letter?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "State the vendor name, the GSTIN or account code, the balance as per books on a stated cut-off date, and whether it is payable or receivable, then ask the vendor to confirm or state the difference and return a signed copy. A line reading balance payable Rs 4,26,500 as on 31 March 2026 leaves no ambiguity. Attach a ledger extract."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between a positive and a negative balance confirmation?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A positive confirmation asks the vendor to reply whether the balance agrees or not, so silence gives no evidence at all. A negative confirmation asks for a reply only where the balance disagrees, so silence is treated as agreement. Positive confirmations suit large or disputed balances, negative ones only small and numerous balances where risk is low."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is vendor balance confirmation compulsory in an Indian statutory audit?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "It is not compulsory for payables, but SA 505 on external confirmations treats direct confirmation as strong audit evidence and auditors routinely seek it for major creditors. Where a vendor does not reply, alternative procedures such as checking payments made after year end and goods receipt notes are performed. Confirmations also support the Schedule III trade payables ageing."
          }
        }
      ]
